4":"1204","December 1197":"december 1197","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1212":"omkring 1212","about 1177":"omkring 1177","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1177–about 1212":"circa 1177–circa 1212","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1146–1204":"1146–1204","1 November 1197":"1 november 1197","1204":"1204","December 1197":"december 1197","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1212":"circa 1212","about 1177":"circa 1177","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1177–about 1212":"about 1177–about 1212","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1146–1204":"1146–1204","1 November 1197":"1 November 1197","1204":"1204","December 1197":"December 1197","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1212":"about 1212","about 1177":"about 1177","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathew de Holland was born about 1177, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England as the son of Siward Simon de Holland Of Longworth. He had at least 1 son with Margaret de Harcourt. He died about 1212, in his hometown, at the age of 37."},"et":{"about 1177–about 1212":"umbes 1177–umbes 1212","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1146–1204":"1146–1204","1 November 1197":"1. november 1197","1204":"1204","December 1197":"detsember 1197","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","about 1212":"umbes 1212","about 1177":"umbes 1177","Up Holland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1177–about 1212":"noin 1177–noin 1212","1177–1212":"1177–1212","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1197–1242":"1197–1242","1146–1204":"1146–1204","1 November 1197":"1. marraskuuta 1197","1204":"1204","December 1197":"joulukuu 1197","1146":"1146","1212":"1212","1